<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1924-03-06T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1924-03-06T13:00:00-05:00" n="185" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d185">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">811.2300/68: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Kellogg</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-03-06T18:00:00+00:00"><hi rend="italic">March 6,
                                        1924—6 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received March 6—2:42
                                p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>87. My telegram no. 61, February 15, 4 p.m., <hi rend="italic">re</hi>
                            world aeroplane flight. The British Government agrees to waive usual
                            restrictions on aerial photography in the case of the five aeroplanes,
                            provided they do not fly over or photograph any of prohibited areas
                            named in schedule 7 of Air Navigation Order 1923, copy of which I am
                            forwarding you,<note n="24" xml:id="d185fn24">Not printed.</note> or the
                            areas in which armament depots are situated at Woolwich, Bedenham,
                            Marchwood, Bandeath and Wrabness.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Kellogg</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>